  <title>umrs-ls — High-Assurance Directory Listing</title>

  <p>
    <cmd>umrs-ls</cmd> lists the contents of a directory grouped by SELinux security type
    and marking. It is designed for operators and security auditors who need to verify
    the security posture of filesystem objects — not just see their names.
  </p>

  <p>
    The key difference from <cmd>ls -Z</cmd> is <em>how</em> the security label is obtained.
    Standard <cmd>ls</cmd> uses a path-based syscall (<sys>lstat</sys>) that asks the kernel
    for a label by filename. <cmd>umrs-ls</cmd> attempts to <sys>open()</sys> each object and
    anchors all subsequent metadata reads — including the SELinux xattr — to that single
    file descriptor. If <sys>open()</sys> is denied, the entry is marked
    <code>&lt;restricted&gt;</code> rather than showing an unverified path-derived label.
  </p>

